05659nam a22007575i 9780812294576DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20172018pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122945767 a10.9783/97808122945762doi  a(DE-B1597)493762  a(OCoLC)1030295797  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aPOL0330002bisacsh04a320.55/72231 aKaragiannis, Emmanuel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe New Political Islam :bHuman Rights, Democracy, and Justice /cEmmanuel Karagiannis. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2017] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b6 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHaney Foundation Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tPART I. Islamist Activism and the Master Frame of Human Rights -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. The Activism of European Converts -- tChapter 2. The Activism of Hizb ut-Tahrir -- tPART II. Islamist Politics and the Master Frame of Democracy -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 3. The Politics of Islamo-Democracy in Turkey, Egypt, and Tunisia -- tChapter 4. The Politics of Electoral Salafism in Egypt and Tunisia -- tPART III. Islamist Militancy and the Master Frame of Justice -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 5. The Militancy of Shia Groups in Lebanon, Iraq, and Syria -- tChapter 6. The Militancy of Sunni Groups in Iraq and Syria -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIslamist political parties and groups are on the rise throughout the Muslim world and in Muslim communities in the West. Owing largely to the threat of terrorism, political Islam is often portrayed as a monolithic movement embodying fundamentalism and theocracy, an image magnified by the rise of populism and xenophobia in the United States and Europe. Reality, however, is far more complicated. Political Islam has evolved considerably since its spectacular rise decades ago, and today it features divergent viewpoints and contributes to discrete but simultaneous developments worldwide. This is a new political Islam, more global in scope but increasingly local in action.Emmanuel Karagiannis offers a sophisticated analysis of the different manifestations of contemporary Islamism. In a context of global economic and social changes, he finds local manifestations of Islamism are becoming both more prevalent and more diverse. Many Islamists turn to activism, still more participate formally in the democratic process, and some, in far fewer numbers, advocate violence—a wide range of political persuasions and tactics that reflects real and perceived political, cultural, and identity differences.Synthesizing prodigious research and integrating insights from the globalization debate and the literature on social movements, The New Political Islam seeks to explain the processes and factors leading to distinctive fusions of "the global" and "the local" across the landscape of contemporary political Islam. Examining converts to Islam in Europe, nonviolent Islamists with global reach, Islamist parties in Turkey, Egypt, and Tunisia, and militant Shia and Sunni groups in Syria and Iraq, Karagiannis demonstrates that Islamists have embraced ideas and practices from the global marketplace and have attempted to implement them locally. He looks closely at the ways in which Islamist activists, politicians, and militants have utilized the language of human rights, democracy, and justice to gain influence and popular support and to contend for power.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aDemocracyxReligious aspectsxIslam. 0aHuman rights advocacyxReligious aspectsxIslam. 0aIslam and politicsxHistoryy21st century. 0aIslamic fundamentalismy21st century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Globalization.2bisacsh  aPolitical Science.  aPublic Policy.  aReligion.  aReligious Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDTL Humanities 2020z978311073776908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060663840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081229457640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812294576423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812294576.jpg  a978-3-11-060663-8  University of Pennsylvania Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-073776-9  DTL Humanities 2020b2020  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK